FWIW, much of the verbosity in this post is optional, e.g. the very first example could be<p><pre><code>  static mut base: uint = 0x200000;
  pub extern &quot;C&quot; fn malloc(len: uint) -> *mut u8 {
      base as *mut u8
  }
</code></pre>
(I&#x27;ll admit the second can be reduced less, since it&#x27;s actually doing real work: basically just dropping the `: uint` on the `let ret`, dropping the `return` and associated `;`, and removing the () on the if condition.)<p>I guess the major source of verbosity is the `extern &quot;C&quot;`, which, fortunately, is only necessary when one <i>requires</i> a function uses the C ABI/calling-convention; in the overwhelmingly common case one writes `pub fn foo(...)` which will use the Rust ABI (and it gets reduced to just `fn foo(...)` if the function can be private to a module).
